A Gentle Introduction To Rust Async

4 steps

In this short tutorial, you will learn the basic concepts of asynchronous programming in Rust. You will learn why this is important, and when and when not to use async features.

Let's learn!

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Recommended to have finished Speedrun Rust.
  • Recommended to have finished some Rust Basics tutorials.
  • A working Rust installation. For instructions, head to https://rustup.rs/ and follow the platform-specific instructions.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Explain basic concepts of asynchronous programming
  • Know when and where async is used
  • Write basic async code in Rust

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 4

  • Step 1: Defining Asynchronous Programming

    There are various methodologies that can be used to run tasks independently. In some cases, tasks may depend on one another, while in other scenarios, they can operate entirely independently. Often, a combination of both is observed, as tasks may be grouped together depending on the contextfor instance, uploading files while simultaneously maintaining a graphical user interface. These are two distinct processes that can be handled concurrently.

    In asynchronous programming, tasks are designed in such a way that they allow other tasks to continue executing while they themselves are still in progress. This means that each line of execution that spawns a new task is not required to wait for the previous task to complete before proceeding.

    This concept may initially seem confusing. Consider the analogy of a head chef in a busy kitchen. Several tasks are assigned:

    • Chopping vegetables and spices
    • Frying meat
    • Boiling water

    Each of these tasks requires a different amount of time to completefor example, boiling water might take five minutes, chopping vegetables just one minute, and frying meat eight minutes. These tasks must all be completed before the final dish can be assembled and served. Thus, they are awaited, and the overall execution is not considered complete until all have finished.

    Such tasks are considered to be executed asynchronously. They are carried out concurrently, with each having its own duration, yet all contribute to a single end goal. Despite being executed at the same time, their dependency on one anotherdue to their role in the final dishstill remains.

    This differs significantly from synchronous programming, where execution is blocking. In synchronous models, a task must be completed before the next one can begin. 

    In contrast, asynchronous programming allows tasks to operate independently, without needing to wait for others to finishmaking it a non-blocking approach.

    In traditional (synchronous) programming, if your program is doing something that takes time like loading a file from disk or fetching data from the internet it pauses everything else until that task is finished. This is fine for small scripts, but in large or interactive applications (like web servers or user interfaces), waiting around becomes a problem.

    As another example, imagine a restaurant where the chef stops cooking every time they wait for a dish to bake. Thats blocking. Async is like the chef working on other dishes while somethings in the oven.

    In the next step, you will be going over some code examples and explanations for how async works in Rust.

  • Step 2: Basic Async Code Examples with Tokio

    Asynchronous programming in Rust is built around the idea of futures values that represent work that hasn't finished yet.

    At the core:

    • async fn defines an asynchronous function that returns a Future
    • await pauses execution until that future is complete.
    • You need an executor (like tokio, async-std, or smol) to run async code.

    Before starting to test the code examples, ensure that you have followed the prerequisites listed for the tutorial. Come back here once you are done.

    Run the following commands.

    cargo new --edition 2021 async-rust
cd async-rust
cargo add tokio -F full

    This should do the following:

    • Create a new directory and Rust project called async-rust.
    • Change directory to async-rust.
    • Add a new crate dependency called tokio with crate feature "full" enabled.

    Tokio is an asynchronous runtime for Rust. It provides the tools needed to write non-blocking, highly concurrent applications especially ones that deal with lots of I/O like servers, clients, and real-time systems.

    Tokio is what makes async Rust actually run. Its like the engine under the hood that schedules and manages your async tasks. Rusts standard library supports async/await, but it doesnt include a built-in runtime to actually execute async code. Thats where Tokio comes in.

    use std::time::Duration;
use tokio::time::sleep;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    println!("Start");
    
    my_async_function().await;

    println!("End");
}

async fn my_async_function() {
    sleep(Duration::from_secs(2)).await;
    println!("Done waiting!");
}
    Rust

    The following code example entails the following:

    • tokio::main sets up the runtime to run async code.
    • sleep().await simulates waiting for something (like a network call).
    • The rest of the program can keep running during that wait.

    You can spawn new tasks at the same time to await while not blocking other tasks.

    use tokio::time::{sleep, Duration};

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let task1 = async {
        sleep(Duration::from_secs(2)).await;
        println!("Task 1 done");
    };

    let task2 = async {
        sleep(Duration::from_secs(2)).await;
        println!("Task 2 done");
    };

    tokio::join!(task1, task2);
    println!("Both tasks finished");
}
    Rust

    You can also spawn a new task as a background task with spawn.

    use tokio::time::{sleep, Duration};

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    tokio::spawn(async {
        sleep(Duration::from_secs(1)).await;
        println!("Background task finished");
    });

    println!("Main function is done");
    sleep(Duration::from_secs(2)).await; // give time for the spawned task
}
    Rust

    However, the code comes with a behaviour you should be familiar with. If the background task takes longer, its operation might be dropped before it can fully execute. For example, the new code won't print "Background task finished" unlike before.

    use tokio::time::{sleep, Duration};

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    tokio::spawn(async {
        sleep(Duration::from_secs(5)).await;
        println!("Background task finished");
    });

    println!("Main function is done");
    sleep(Duration::from_secs(4)).await; // give time for the spawned task
}
    Rust
  • Step 3: What Now?

    Currently, the examples are too simple to give you a full idea of what asynchronous programming truly entails. While they help illustrate the basic mechanics of async and await, they don't yet reflect the complexity or practical challenges you'll encounter in real-world applications.

    In practice, asynchronous code is not always needed in fact, most general-purpose code runs synchronously just fine. This is because many tasks are CPU-bound or simple enough that introducing async would add unnecessary complexity.

    However, asynchronous programming becomes essential when dealing with I/O-bound operations tasks that spend most of their time waiting for external resources. This includes things like reading or writing files, making network or web requests, handling user input events, or drawing graphical elements to the screen.

    For example, in a desktop application, async allows the user interface to stay responsive while data is being loaded in the background. In a game engine, it helps load assets or generate procedural elements without stalling the rendering loop.

    In web servers, async is crucial for handling thousands of simultaneous requests without consuming excessive resources. By allowing the system to process other tasks while waiting for a response (like from a database or API), async improves scalability and efficiency dramatically.

    Understanding when and where to use async effectively is part of designing responsive, efficient, and user-friendly systems especially in applications that need to do many things at once without freezing up or wasting system resources.
